    "refcode_long": "The Adventist Home, p. 52.2 (Ellen Gould White)",
    "element_type": "p",
    "element_subtype": "standard-indented",
    "content": "Daughters are not taught self-denial and self-control. They are petted, and their pride is fostered. They are allowed to have their own way, until they become headstrong and self-willed, and you are put to your wits&rsquo; end to know what course to pursue to save them from ruin. Satan is leading them on to be a proverb in the mouth of unbelievers because of their boldness, their lack of reserve and womanly modesty. The young boys are likewise left to have their own way. They have scarcely entered their teens before they are by the side of little girls of their own age, accompanying them home and making love to them. And the parents are so completely in bondage through their own indulgence and mistaken love for their children that they dare not pursue a decided course to make a change and restrain their too-fast children in this fast age.<sup class=\"chapterendnote\"><a class=\"chapterendnote\">12<span class=\"chapterendnote\"><span class=\"egwlink egwlink_book\" title=\"2T 460.1\" data-link=\"120.2002\">Ibid., 2:460</span>.</span></a></sup>",
